409–1482":"1409–1482","7 June 1482":"7 juni 1482","Abt 1409":"circa 1409","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1409":"1409","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Belton, Haddington, Scotland":"East Lothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland":"Borthwick, Midlothian, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Woodhall, Scotland":"Woodhall, Renfrewshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1409–7 June 1482":"about 1409–7 June 1482","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1439–1529":"1439–1529","1409–1482":"1409–1482","7 June 1482":"7 June 1482","Abt 1409":"about 1409","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1409":"1409","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Belton, Haddington, Scotland":"East Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland":"Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Woodhall, Scotland":"Woodhall, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cunningham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the province of Cunningham in Ayrshire, first recorded in 1153 in the form <i>Cunegan</i>, a Celtic name of uncertain origin. The spellings in <i>-ham</i>, first recorded in 1180, and in <i>-ynghame</i>, first recorded in 1227, represent a gradual assimilation to the English placename element <i>-ingham</i>.","Irish: surname adopted from Gaelic <b>Ó Cuinneagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuinneagán</i>’, a personal name from a double diminutive of the Old Irish personal name <i>Conn</i> meaning ‘leader, chief’. This name is also adopted for <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Connagán</i>’, from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Conn</i>.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Wernebald de Cunynghame, who was granted the manor of Cunningham by Hugh de Morville in the early 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Cunigan","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish or Irish   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Conahan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac.","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Connachaín</b> (see   Cunningham  )."]},{"name":"Conaghan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac, Fergal.","Scottish (Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire) Irish (Donegal): from <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b>, see   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cuningham","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cummingham","meanings":["(1997: 117;2007: 199; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cunnigham","meanings":["(2007: 429; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish (Donegal): variant of   Cunningham  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir George Cunningham Lord of Belton was born about 1409, in East Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Anna de Montgomery. He died on 7 June 1482, in Woodhall, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 74."},"et":{"Abt 1409–7 June 1482":"umbes 1409–7. juuni 1482","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1439–1529":"1439–1529","1409–1482":"1409–1482","7 June 1482":"7. juuni 1482","Abt 1409":"umbes 1409","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1409":"1409","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Belton, Haddington, Scotland":"East Lothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland":"Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Woodhall, Scotland":"Woodhall, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1409–7 June 1482":"noin 1409–7. kesäkuuta 1482","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1439–1529":"1439–1529","1409–1482":"1409–1482","7 June 1482":"7. kesäkuuta 1482","Abt 1409":"noin 1409","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1409":"1409","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Belton, Haddington, Scotland":"East Lothian, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland":"Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Woodhall, Scotland":"Woodhall, Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1409–7 June 1482":"environ 1409–7 juin 1482","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1439–1529":"1439–1529","1409–1482":"1409–1482","7 June 1482":"7 juin 1482","Abt 1409":"environ 1409","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1409":"1409","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Belton, Haddington, Scotland":"East Lothian, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland":"Borthwick, Midlothian, Écosse","Scotland":"Écosse","Woodhall, Scotland":"Woodhall, Renfrewshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir George Cunningham Lord of Belton est né environ 1409, à East Lothian, Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Anna de Montgomery. Il est décédé le 7 juin 1482, à Woodhall, Ren